.TH DRV_HZTOUSEC 9 "@PACKAGE_DATE@" "@PACKAGE@-@VERSION@" "@PACKAGE_TITLE@ DDI/DKI"
.\"
.\"
.SH NAME
.B drv_hztousec, drv_usectohz, drv_hztomsec, drv_msectohz
\- convert kernel tick time between microseconds or milliseconds
.\"
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #include <sys/types.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/dki.h>
.HP
.BI "clock_t drv_hztousec(clock_t " hertz );
.PD 0
.HP
.BI "clock_t drv_hztomsec(clock_t " hertz );
.HP
.BI "clock_t drv_usectohz(clock_t " usec );
.HP
.BI "clock_t drv_msectohz(clock_t " msec );
.PD
.\"
.\"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I hertz
the time value in ticks to convert to milliseconds or microseconds.
.TP
.I usec
the time value in microseconds to convert to ticks.
.TP
.I msec
the time value in milliseconds to convert to ticks.
.\"
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec ()
.BR drv_hztomsec ()
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
provide a mechanism for converting between kernel tick time and an absolute
time unit (microseconds or milliseconds).  Use of these functions permit
driver code to be architecturally independent from the quantum of the kernel
tick clock.
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec ()
accepts a kernel tick clock time as the
.I hertz
argument and returns the time in microseconds.
.BR drv_hztomsec ()
accepts a kernel tick clock time as the
.I hertz
argument and returns the time in milliseconds.
.BR drv_usectohz ()
accepts a time interval in microseconds in the
.I usec
argument and returns the time in clock ticks.
.BR drv_msectohz ()
accepts a time interval in milliseconds in the
.I msec
argument and returns the time in clock ticks.
.PP
These functions are useful in conjunction with
.BR timeout (9)
and
.BR qtimeout (9)
which only accept timeout durations in system ticks.
.\"
.\"
.SH RETURN
.PP
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
return the time value in ticks.
.BR drv_hztousec ()
returns the time value in microseconds.
.BR drv_hztomsec ()
returns the time value in milliseconds.
.\"
.\"
.SH ERRORS
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec (),
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
always succeed.
.\"
.\"
.SH CONTEXT
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec (),
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
can be called from any context, including user context, module procedures,
callouts, callbacks, soft interrupts and interrupt service routines.
.\"
.\"
.SH MP-STREAMS
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec (),
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
are MP safe.
.\"
.\"
.SH NOTICES
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec (),
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
are implemented by performing simple calculations using
.BR jiffies (9)
and
.BR HZ (9).
There are defined as
.B extern inline
functions and with optimization these calculations will be inline.
.PP
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
always round up to the next highest integer tick value.  This ensures that,
when converting a value less than a tick, the result will always be 1 tick.
This makes these functions safe for use with
.BR timeout (9)
and
.BR qtimeout (9).
.PP
Care should be taken with the
.BR drv_hztousec ()
function, as coverted value can easily overflow a
.BR clock_t .
Portable
.I STREAMS
modules and drivers will only convert differences between successive calls to
.BR drv_getparm (9)
or retrieval of
.BR lbolt (9)
with
.BR drv_hztousec ()
instead of converting each value and then taking the difference.
.\"
.\"
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.PP
.BR drv_getparm (9),
.BR ddi_get_lbolt (9),
.BR ddi_get_time (9).
.\"
.\"
.SH BUGS
.PP
These functions have no known bugs in
.B LfS\c
.
.[
LfS
.]
.\"
.\"
.SH COMPATIBILITY
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec (),
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ()
are source-level compatible with
.IR "SVR 4.2 MP DDI/DKI" ,
.[
usldk
.]
and implementations based on
.IR "SVR 4.2" ,
.[
svr42
.]
with the following portability considerations:
.IP \(em \w'\(em\(em'u
.I LiS
.[
LiS
.]
does not provide these functions.
.I LiS
provide a completely non-standard and non-portable set of functions,
.BR lis_time_till (9),
.BR lis_target_time (9),
.BR liz_usectohz (9),
and
.BR lis_milli_to_ticks (9).
Of these,
.BR lis_uzectohz (9)
and
.BR lis_milli_to_ticks (9)
are equivalent to
.BR drv_usectohz ()
and
.BR drv_msectohz ().
.IP \(em
Later
.B Linux
kernels provide the functions
.BR jiffies_to_msecs (9),
.BR msecs_to_jiffies (9),
and
.BR jiffies_to_usecs (9),
and these are used where available to implement
.BR drv_hztomsec (),
.BR drv_msectohz (),
and
.BR drv_hztousec (),
respectively.
.IP \(em
Binary compatibility is not guaranteed.
.PP
See
.BR STREAMS (9)
for additional compatibility information.
.\"
.\"
.SH CONFORMANCE
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec "() and " drv_usectohz ()
conform to
.IR "SVR 4.2 MP DDI/DKI" .
.[
usldk
.]
.PP
.BR drv_hztomsec "() and " drv_msectohz ()
are
.B Linux Fast-STREAMS
specific.
.\"
.\"
.SH HISTORY
.PP
.BR drv_hztousec "() and " drv_usectohz ()
first appeared in SVR 4.
.[
svr4
.]
